flict marked by inequality and negotiation over income and expenditures. Dwyer and Bruce's introduction is followed by eleven field studies: four in Asia, four in Africa and the Middle East, and three in the Caribbean and Central America. These twelve essays, by economists, sociologists, anthropologists and demographers provide a cogent analysis of household structure dynamics and women's bargaining context. This book will be of interest not only to specialists in gender studies but also to ethnologists and other social scientists.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 4aSociology -- Race, Class, and Gender. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aBruce, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBruce, Judith, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCain, Mead, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDwyer, Daisy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDwyer, Daisy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFapohunda, Eleanor R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFolbre, Nancy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreenhalgh, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuyer, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoodfar, Homa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMencher, Joan P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMunachonga, Monica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPapanek, Hanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPessar, Patricia R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRolda